T1  - The Macroeconomic Impact of Climate Change: Global Versus Local Temperature*
PY  - 2026
Y1  - 2026/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjag011
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 141
IS  - 2
SP  - 889
EP  - 944
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This article estimates that the macroeconomic damages from climate change are an order of magnitude larger than previously thought. Exploiting natural global temperature variability, we find that 1ºC warming reduces world GDP by over 20% in the long run. Global temperature correlates strongly with extreme climatic events, unlike country-level temperature used in previous work, explaining our larger estimate. We use this evidence to estimate damage functions in a neoclassical growth model. Business-as-usual warming implies a present welfare loss of more than 30%, and a social cost of carbon in excess of $1,200 per ton. These impacts suggest that unilateral decarbonization policy is cost-effective for large countries such as the United States.
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjag011
ER  - 




